    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n`vim.pack.add()` with `version = vim.version.range('*')` is too permissive at what tags it treats as semver. For example, `nvim-0.6` will be treated as a tag for `0.6.0` version.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. `NVIM_APPNAME=nvim-new nvim`\n2. `:lua vim.pack.add({ { src = 'https://github.com/nvim-telescope/telescope.nvim', version = vim.version.range('*') } })`. It installs at tag `nvim-0.6`, but the greatest semver tag is `v0.2.2` (as of time of this writing).\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nOnly tags that were intended to convey semver information about the plugin should be considered when `version` is a `VersionRange` object. The problem is to find a balance between flexibility and false positives. There are several approaches:\n\n1. The easiest one is to use `vim.version.parse(x, { strict = true })` when [deciding if the tag is semver tag](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/d393975b04e9226dbf4a8ec3eea75a62d37d7594/runtime/lua/vim/pack.lua#L346). The problem here is that tags like `v1`, `v1.0`, `1.0`, `1-0-0` won't be considered a semver tag. Although technically true, I think tags without minor and/or patch numbers should still be considered semver.\n2. Use some ad-hoc pattern matching when deciding if a tag is semver. Maybe something like `x:find('^v?%d+$') or x:find('^v?%d+%.%d+$') or x:find('^v%d+%.%d+%.%d+$')`. Seems okay.\n3. Adjust `vim.version.parse(x, { strict = true })` to allow `1` and `1.0` as valid semver. Technically, it is breaking.\n\nBoth 1 and 2 are fine with me and will technically not be breaking for `vim.pack`, since `v<major>.<minor>.<patch>` convention for tags [is documented](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/d393975b04e9226dbf4a8ec3eea75a62d37d7594/runtime/lua/vim/pack.lua#L15). The only question is how much flexibility for tags to allow here. @justinmk?\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.1\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, doesn't have this functionality\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nEndeavourOS Linux x86_64, 6.19.11-arch1-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.3.1-arch2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nAppimage",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
