            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> > Adjust `vim.version.parse(x, { strict = true })` to allow `1` and `1.0` as valid semver\n> \n> That's no longer \"strict\" then :)\n\nWell, the current \"strict\" is not quite strict, as it [should not treat `vx.y.z.` as semver](https://semver.org/#is-v123-a-semantic-version). So it feels like more up to what's more practical to treat as strict.\n\nMy question is more along the lines of should `vim.pack` treat `1` / `v1` / `1.0` / `v1.0` as semver tags? If yes, then it can be done without adjusting `vim.version.parse`. Or is it more important to align with what `vim.version.parse(x, { strict = true })` says a semver is?\n\nCase in point, some tpope's plugins use `vx.y` tags: ['vim-fugitive'](https://github.com/tpope/vim-fugitive/tags), ['vim-surround'](https://github.com/tpope/vim-surround/tags). Although ['copilot.nvim'](https://github.com/github/copilot.vim/tags) does use semver.",
